/target
Cargo.lock.bak

# Python
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*$py.class
.venv/
venv/
.env
*.egg-info/

# Crawl outputs.
#
# `packs/raw/` and `packs/normalized/` stay out of git — they
# hold the raw HTML/PDF bytes and the normalised markdown that
# (a) are large enough to bloat the repo and (b) are not
# necessarily redistributable for every rights code.
#
# The JSONL outputs ARE committed: `packs/metadata/*.jsonl`,
# `packs/chunks/*.jsonl`, and `packs/governance/*.jsonl`. They
# encode the chunked text + provenance and form the canonical
# input the Rust `pack-build` CLI consumes. Committing them
# gives reviewers an auditable record of *what* was crawled at
# each PR and lets ``pack-build`` reproduce the .pack file
# deterministically.
packs/raw/**/*
packs/normalized/**/*
!packs/**/.gitkeep

# Built pack artifacts.
#
# By default we keep .pack binaries out of git — they're large
# and the canonical distribution channel is GitHub Release
# assets attached at each tagged version (so downstream
# consumers don't need git-lfs or a deep clone).
#
# Exception: ``packs/sn-mdm-tranche1.pack`` IS tracked at the
# repo root packs/ directory. The Devin GitHub App can push
# commits but lacks the ``contents: write`` scope needed to
# publish release assets, so the in-tree copy is the only
# distribution path available until the App permission is
# granted. The committed .pack is rebuildable from the JSONL
# trees under ``packs/{metadata,chunks,governance}/`` via the
# ``pack-build`` CLI — see crates/pack_core/src/bin/pack_build.rs.
# Treat it as a derived artefact that happens to live in-tree
# rather than as source of truth.
*.pack
*.pack.idx
!packs/sn-mdm-tranche1.pack

# Editor / OS
.DS_Store
.idea/
.vscode/
